nversations between researchers and participants","Large community forums with over 20 participants"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key characteristic of focus groups is that they are \u003Cstrong\u003Estructured group discussions with 6-12 participants led by a moderator\u003C/strong\u003E. This format allows for dynamic interaction between participants while remaining manageable enough for meaningful discussion and equal participation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWritten surveys completed by groups of participants\u003C/strong\u003E would not capture the rich verbal interaction and spontaneous responses that characterise focus groups.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIndividual interviews conducted simultaneously in a group setting\u003C/strong\u003E would not allow for group interaction and shared meaning-making that makes focus groups valuable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInformal conversations between researchers and participants\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect, as focus groups require structure and skilled moderation to be effective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge community forums with over 20 participants\u003C/strong\u003E are too unwieldy for effective moderation and meaningful participation from all members.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe moderator\u0027s role is to guide discussion using prepared questions while encouraging natural conversation flow and ensuring all participants have opportunities to contribute. The group dynamic often reveals insights that might not emerge in individual interviews.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Focus groups are structured discussions with 6-12 participants led by a trained moderator to gather qualitative data on specific topics.","Focus groups allow exploration of group dynamics, shared experiences, and diverse perspectives that may not emerge in individual interviews.","The moderator\u0027s role is to facilitate discussion without leading participants while ensuring all voices are heard."],"references":["Then et al. Focus group research: what is it and how can it be used?, https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24660275/, 2014"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62896"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17451"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62896"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T21:22:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T23:57:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10141"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77389"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t